	<p>
		We found that in many cities in Bolivia the people seemed rude. This is for many reasons, I’m sure, but one of our tour guides explained one of the reasons to us. Bolivia is currently the poorest country in South America and when they see tourists they do not think of the potential economic benefit, they think that we are spoiled and rich. Which, let’s be honest, if we’re travelling we are more privileged than most in Bolivia. This means that when we want to bargain with the vendors it pisses them off. Now, that’s not to say you shouldn’t bargain, in fact you should. If you don’t bargain, you will get ripped off - horribly! But, bare this in mind if you are getting ignored or getting rude responses. 
	</p>
	<p>
		We also know that a lot of our problems stemmed from the fact that we did not speak Spanish well at all. You will be taken more seriously if you speak Spanish. Take lessons! 
	</p>
